== The chemical properties of the halogen elements and the hydrogen halides
#point[Describe the relative reactivity of the elements as oxidising agents]
As described above, the electronegativity of the elements decreases down the group. As a result,
the ability of the element to gain electrons, or be reduced, or act as an oxidising agent, also
decreases.

Thus, it follows that _the oxidising power of the halogens decreases going down Group 17._

#point[Describe the reactions of the elements with hydrogen and explain their relative reactivity 
in these reactions]
The halogens form halogen halides when combined with hydrogen gas.
- Fluorine reacts explosively even in cool, dark conditions
$ #ch("H2  (g) + F2  (g) -> 2HF (g)") $
- Chlorine reacts explosively in sunlight
$ #ch("H2  (g) + Cl2  (g) -> 2HCl (g)") $
#pagebreak()
- Bromine reacts slowly on heating
$ #ch("H2  (g) + Br2  (g) -> 2HBr (g)") $
- Iodine forms an equilibrium mixture on heating
$ #ch("H2  (g) + I2  (g) <=> 2HI (g)") $
Note that the vigour of reaction decreases down the group.

#point[
Describe the relative thermal stabilities of the hydrogen halides and explain these in terms of
bond strengths
]
The strength of the #ch("H--X") bond, where X is a halogen, decreases down the group for reasons
discussed above. The strength of a bond is related directly to its bond energy. Down the group,
the bond energy of the #ch("H--X") decreases.

As a result, the thermal stability of a hydrogen halide decreases down the group. The general
equation of the thermal decomposition of a hydrogen halide is as below
$ #ch("2HX (g) -> H2  (g) + X2  (g)  ") $

== Some reactions of the halide ions
#point[Describe the relative reactivity of halide ions as reducing agents]
Same as in the case for elements, _reactivity of halide ions as reducing agents decreases down the
group_.

