#centrebold[Aqueous silver ions followed by aqueous ammonia]\
The above reaction may act as a test for the halide ions. Addition of aqueous ions gives the
following observations in presence of the following halide ions
- White precipitate of silver chloride forms in presence of chloride.
- Cream precipitate  of silver bromide forms in presence of bromine.
- Yellow precipitate of silver iodide forms in presence of iodide.
Addition of aqueous ammonia causes dissolution of the precipitates to varying extents.
- White precipitate of silver chloride dissolves completely in presence of aqueous ammonia.
- Cream precipitate of silver bromide dissolves completely in presence of aqueous ammonia.
- Yellow precipitate of silver iodide dissolves completely in presence of aqueous ammonia.

== The reactions of chlorine
#point[
Describe and interpret, in terms of changes in oxidation number, the reaction of chlorine with cold
and with hot aqueous sodium hydroxide and recognise these as disproportionation reactions
]
#centrebold[With cold aqeuous sodium hydroxide]\
The reaction is
$ #ch("Cl2  (aq) + 2NaOH (aq) -> NaCl (aq) + NaClO (aq) + H2O (l)") $
note that, the oxidation state of chlorine goes from 0 to $-1$ in NaCl and from 0 to $+1$ in
NaClO. This reaction is said to be a disproportionation reaction as chlorine is both oxidised and
reduced. The ionic equation is
$ #ch("Cl2  (aq)+2OH-  (aq) -> Cl-  (aq) + ClO-  (aq) + H2O (l)") $

#centrebold[With hot aqueous sodium hydroxide]\
$ #ch("3Cl2  (aq) + 6NaOH (aq) -> 5NaCl (aq) + NaClO3  (aq) + 3H2O (l)") $
note that, the oxidation state of chlorine goes from 0 to -1 in NaCl and from 0 to +5 in
#ch("NaClO3"). A disproportionation reaction occurs here too.

#point[
Explain, including by use of an equation, the use of chlorine in water purification to include 
the production of the active species #ch("HOCl") and #ch("ClO-") which kill bacteria
]
Water is chlorinated by the following reaction
$ #ch("Cl2  (aq) + H2O (l) -> HCl (aq) + HClO (aq)") $
note that, the oxidation state of chlorine goes from 0 to -1 in HCl and from 0 to +1 in HClO
(called chloric (I) acid). The #ch("ClO-") ion, which forms when the chloric (I) acid dissociates
in water, kills bacteria and hence, a small amount of chlorine is added into the central water
supply to sanitise the water supply.
